scenarioDescription:
The Kepler-35 Exoplanetary System


Overview

Kepler-35 is a star with 0.89 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.03 times its radius. It is located 5365.27 light years away from the solar system.

Kepler-35 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the Kepler-35 system


Kepler-35 b

Kepler-35 b was discovered by the Kepler observatory using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.60 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of Kepler-35 b is 40.386 times the mass of Earth. The radius of Kepler-35 b is 8.16 that of Earth. At more than 10 Earth masses, Kepler-35 b is an ice giant, a planet that is made up mostly of volatiles like water, amonia and methane, and enveloped by a dense hydrogen and helium atmosphere, much like Uranus and Neptune in our solar system.
